Kadane’s Algorithm
--> Kadane’s Algorithm is used to find the maximum sum of a contiguous subarray in a one-dimensional array, in linear time O(n).

Core Idea:
--> Instead of checking all possible subarrays (which is expensive), Kadane’s algorithm works by building the solution as it scans the array once.

Process: 
--> Maintain two variables:
    current_sum → sum of the current subarray you are considering
    max_sum → best (maximum) sum found so far
--> Iterate through the array:
        At each element, decide:
          --> Should you extend the current subarray
          --> OR start a new subarray from this element
--> Decision rule:
    --> If adding the current element improves current_sum, continue
    --> If current_sum becomes worse than starting fresh, reset it
--> Update global maximum:
     After processing each element, compare:
         max_sum = max(max_sum, current_sum)


Key Insight:
--> A negative running sum is harmful, because it will reduce any future sum
--> So we discard it and restart


Intuition (Important):
Kadane’s is basically: 
      “Carry forward profit, drop loss immediately.”

It’s a greedy + dynamic programming hybrid:
    --> Greedy → make best local decision
    --> DP → reuse previous computation


Complexity
Time: O(n)
Space: O(1)


Pattern Recognition Cheat Sheet:
    If question says:
      “contiguous”
      “subarray”
      “maximum/minimum sum”
